[Black-spot disease is a parasitic infection in fish caused by metacercariae of digenetic trematodes belonging to the Family Diplostomidae (hence, the disease is also known as diplopstomiasis). These trematode flukes are expected to thrive in warm temperatures. Research shows that black spot infection rates in fish increases with maximum water temperature. As climate changes make temperatures of water bodies warmer, it is possible that this and other group of parasites are favored and proliferate, while their hosts become more vulnerable

For a picture of a fish with black spot disease compared go to https://huntfish.mdc.mo.gov/sites/default/files/styles/detail/public/media/page/2-Flukes-Oregon-Dept-of-Fish-and-Wildlife%2C-Fish-Health-SectionCMYK_0.jpg?itok=xs4VfhKx. - Mod.PMB

